      <!-- Section 1 -->
      <section id="why-shopify-needs-geo" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Why Shopify Stores Need GEO Now</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Generative engines are becoming the first touchpoint in consumer purchasing journeys, and Shopify stores are structurally under-prepared for this shift.</strong>
          Traditional Shopify SEO focuses on ranking product and collection pages for specific keywords. GEO requires a different foundation:
          machine-readable product data, brand entity clarity, and content that AI systems can extract cleanly and cite with confidence.
        </p>

        <p>
          ChatGPT's Shopping integration, Perplexity's product carousels, and Google AI Overviews for commercial queries all pull product
          information from structured sources. Stores that surface in these placements gain zero-click consideration — the shopper receives
          a recommendation before they have visited a single product page. Stores absent from AI answers must compete only at the point
          where users click through to a search results page, a pool that is shrinking as AI-generated answers satisfy more intent without
          requiring further navigation.
        </p>

        <p>
          The good news for Shopify merchants is that the platform provides more GEO leverage than most. Shopify's theme architecture
          allows structured data injection, its metafields system enables rich product attributes, and its app ecosystem includes several
          tools specifically designed to improve schema quality. The challenge is knowing which levers to pull — and in what order.
        </p>

        <p>
          This guide covers Shopify GEO from the theme layer through to app configuration and content strategy.
          For the broader GEO framework that applies across all platforms, see the
          <a href="/generative-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">generative engine optimisation guide</a>.
          For the full industry hub covering other platforms, see
          <a href="/geo-by-industry/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO by industry</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 2 -->
      <section id="theme-schema-control" class="anchor-top mb-16">
        <div class="prose-dark">
          <h2>Theme and Schema Control on Shopify</h2>
          <p>
            <strong>Shopify theme choice directly determines the baseline quality of your store's structured data output.</strong>
            Every Shopify theme that renders product pages injects some form of JSON-LD markup, but the completeness and accuracy of
            that markup varies enormously between themes and even between versions of the same theme.
          </p>

          <h3>What Shopify Themes Generate by Default</h3>
          <p>
            Most modern Shopify themes (Dawn, Sense, Crave, and their commercial equivalents) produce a <code>Product</code> schema block on
            product pages and a <code>BreadcrumbList</code> on collection and product pages. Typically missing are:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>brand</strong> — the manufacturer or brand entity, critical for AI engines resolving product-to-brand relationships</li>
            <li><strong>aggregateRating</strong> — review score and count, which AI engines use to qualify recommendations</li>
            <li><strong>sku</strong> and <strong>gtin</strong> — identifiers that allow AI systems to match your product to external databases</li>
            <li><strong>Organization</strong> schema at the store root — required for brand entity authority</li>
            <li><strong>FAQPage</strong> schema on blog or landing pages — where most buying-intent queries are answered</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>Auditing Your Theme's Schema Output</h3>
          <p>
            Before configuring any schema app, audit what your theme already produces. Use Google's Rich Results Test on a product page,
            a collection page, and your homepage. Note every field that is present, every field that is missing, and any validation errors.
            This baseline audit prevents duplicate or conflicting schema blocks when you add an app layer on top.
          </p>

          <p>
            If your theme is injecting schema in both <code>&lt;script type="application/ld+json"&gt;</code> blocks and via
            microdata attributes, consolidate to JSON-LD only. Mixed schema implementations are a common source of AI parsing errors
            in Shopify stores.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Schema completeness table -->
        <div class="mt-8 overflow-x-auto rounded-xl border border-geo-800">
          <table class="w-full text-sm">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b border-geo-800 bg-geo-900">
                <th scope="col" class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-ink-100">Schema Field</th>
