                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-200 font-mono">Organization (store level)</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-red-400">No</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400">Yes</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">High — brand entity authority</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="hover:bg-geo-900/50 transition">
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-200 font-mono">FAQPage (blog/landing)</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-red-400">No</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400">Yes</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">High — FAQ citation</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="hover:bg-geo-900/50 transition">
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-200 font-mono">BreadcrumbList</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400">Yes</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400">Yes</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Medium — navigation context</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <div class="prose-dark mt-6">
          <p>
            For full schema implementation guidance applicable to any platform, see our
            <a href="/schema-markup-ai/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">schema markup for AI guide</a>.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 3 -->
      <section id="product-data-for-ai" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Product Data Optimisation for AI Engines</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>AI engines do not read product descriptions the way human shoppers do — they parse them for extractable facts, attributes, and definitional claims.</strong>
          A product description written purely for conversion will perform poorly in AI-generated shopping recommendations. Optimising
          product data for AI requires a structural shift in how descriptions are written and how attributes are stored.
        </p>

        <h3>The AI-Readable Product Description Formula</h3>
        <p>
          Open every product description with a single factual statement that defines the product category, primary function, and key
          differentiator. For example: "The Apex Trail Runner is a waterproof fell-running shoe with a 4mm drop, Vibram Megagrip sole,
          and a reinforced toe cap, designed for technical off-road terrain." This opening sentence is immediately extractable by an AI
          engine responding to a query about waterproof trail shoes.
        </p>
        <p>
          The body of the description should then cover: materials and construction, key technical specifications (dimensions, weight,
          compatibility), use-case suitability, and a brief answer to the most common buyer question for that product category.
          Avoid superlatives ("best in class", "market-leading") — these carry no factual content and are filtered out by AI extraction
          logic.
        </p>

        <h3>Metafields as Structured Product Attributes</h3>
        <p>
          Shopify metafields allow merchants to store structured product attributes — material, fit, country of manufacture, certifications —
          that can be exposed to schema markup and surfaced in theme templates. For GEO purposes, metafields are valuable because they
          enable clean, consistent attribute data that schema apps can pull directly into <code>additionalProperty</code> fields on
          Product schema. AI engines that process structured attribute data are more likely to recommend products correctly when
          filtering by specific characteristics.
        </p>
        <p>
          Populate metafields for every product attribute that appears in typical buyer queries for your category. For a clothing store,
          this means material composition, care instructions, sizing standard (UK/EU/US), and certifications. For electronics,
          this means compatibility, connectivity standards, power ratings, and warranty terms.
        </p>

        <h3>Collection Pages and Category Queries</h3>
        <p>
          Collection pages are underutilised in most Shopify GEO strategies. They are the natural answer to category queries —
          "best vegan leather handbags", "waterproof hiking boots for women" — and should be treated as content pages, not
          merely filter interfaces. Each collection page should include a 200–400 word introductory section that defines the category,
          describes what distinguishes this collection, and answers the top two or three questions buyers have at the category level.
          This section feeds directly into AI-generated category recommendations.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 4 -->
      <section id="app-ecosystem" class="anchor-top mb-16">
        <div class="prose-dark">
          <h2>The Shopify App Ecosystem for AI Visibility</h2>
          <p>
            <strong>The right combination of Shopify apps eliminates the structured data gaps that prevent AI engines from citing your store.</strong>
            Each app category addresses a distinct layer of the GEO stack — schema control, review data, content structure, and
            AI crawler guidance.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="mt-8 space-y-5">

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Schema Control Apps</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              <strong>JsonLD for SEO</strong> and <strong>Schema App</strong> are the two most capable structured data apps in the
              Shopify ecosystem. Both allow merchants to configure Product, Organization, FAQPage, Article, and BreadcrumbList schema
              without editing Liquid templates. JsonLD for SEO is generally better suited to merchants who want a code-free setup;
              Schema App offers more granular control for stores with complex product catalogues. Before installing either, disable
              or remove any existing schema injection in your theme to prevent duplicate blocks.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Review and Rating Apps</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              <strong>Judge.me</strong>, <strong>Okendo</strong>, and <strong>Yotpo</strong> all produce <code>aggregateRating</code>
              schema on product pages when configured correctly. This is one of the highest-impact GEO interventions available to
              Shopify merchants, because AI recommendation engines weight products with review data significantly higher than
              unrated products. Configure your review app to output schema on every product page — not just pages with ten or more
              reviews — and verify the output with Google's Rich Results Test after deployment.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">FAQ and Content Structure Apps</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              FAQ sections on product pages directly improve AI citation rates. Apps such as <strong>HelpCenter</strong> and
              <strong>Helpy: Product FAQs</strong> allow merchants to add structured Q&amp;A sections to individual product pages
              or collections. Pair these with FAQPage schema output (either from the app itself or from your schema control app)
              to give AI engines a clean, extractable Q&amp;A layer on every key page.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Metafield Management Apps</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              <strong>Metafields Guru</strong> and Shopify's native metafield editor allow bulk population of product attributes
              that feed into schema markup. For stores with large catalogues, a CSV-based bulk import workflow is essential —
              manually editing metafields product by product is not scalable. Ensure your schema control app is configured to
              read from the correct metafield namespaces when generating Product schema output.
            </p>
          </div>

        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 5 -->
      <section id="llms-txt-shopify" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Deploying llms.txt on Shopify</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>An llms.txt file tells AI crawlers which pages on your store contain the most authoritative, citation-worthy content.</strong>
          For a Shopify store, this typically means your homepage, key collection pages, brand story page, and any editorial or FAQ
          content that answers category-level queries. The challenge is that Shopify's file system does not expose a standard root
          directory, so the usual static-file deployment approach does not apply.
        </p>

        <h3>Method 1: Liquid Template Route</h3>
        <p>
          Create a new Liquid template in your theme (e.g., <code>page.llms-txt.liquid</code>) that outputs plain text rather than
          HTML. Set the page's <code>Content-Type</code> to <code>text/plain</code> using Shopify's template rendering. Create a page
          in the Shopify admin with the handle <code>llms-txt</code> and assign it the new template. Then configure a URL redirect
          from <code>/llms.txt</code> to <code>/pages/llms-txt</code>. This approach requires no external infrastructure and
          is maintainable through the Shopify admin.
        </p>

        <h3>Method 2: Cloudflare Worker Intercept</h3>
        <p>
          If your store is proxied through Cloudflare, a Worker script can intercept requests for <code>/llms.txt</code> and return
          the file content directly, bypassing Shopify entirely. This approach is cleaner — the URL serves exactly as
          <code>/llms.txt</code> with no redirect — and the Worker content is trivially updatable. It requires Cloudflare in the
          DNS chain, which is already the case for most stores using Cloudflare's performance or security features.
        </p>

        <p>
          For full llms.txt implementation guidance including file structure and content strategy, see our
          <a href="/llms-txt/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">llms.txt guide</a>.
        </p>
